    pearls: ["Pulse oximetry is FALSELY NORMAL in CO poisoning — it cannot distinguish COHb from oxyhemoglobin. Always use co-oximetry (venous or arterial) to measure COHb directly", "When multiple household members present with simultaneous 'flu-like' symptoms (headache, nausea), consider CO poisoning and check COHb levels on all patients", "Delayed neurological sequelae (cognitive decline, personality change, parkinsonism) can appear weeks after seemingly full recovery — all significant exposures need neuropsych follow-up"],
