    cellular: { title: "CNS Depression Mechanisms", content: "The sedative-hypnotic toxidrome results from excessive central nervous system depression through enhancement of inhibitory neurotransmission (GABA) or suppression of excitatory neurotransmission (glutamate). Benzodiazepines bind the GABA-A receptor at the benzodiazepine binding site, enhancing chloride channel opening FREQUENCY (not duration — this limits their ceiling effect and accounts for their relative safety in isolated overdose). Barbiturates bind a different GABA-A site, increasing chloride channel opening DURATION and at high doses directly opening channels without GABA — this removes the ceiling effect, explaining their lethality in overdose. GHB (gamma-hydroxybutyrate) activates GHB receptors and GABA-B receptors. Ethanol enhances GABA-A and inhibits NMDA glutamate receptors. The common final pathway is enhanced chloride influx → membrane hyperpolarization → neuronal inhibition → progressive CNS depression from sedation through coma to respiratory arrest." },
